      <div class="tips-categories">
        <!-- General Tips -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-book-reader"></i> General Cooking Tips</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Read the Recipe First</h3>
              <p>Always read through the entire recipe before starting. This helps you understand the process, timing, and what equipment you'll need.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Mise en Place</h3>
              <p>Prep all your ingredients before you start cooking. This French technique means "everything in its place" and makes cooking much smoother.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Taste as You Go</h3>
              <p>Season and taste your food throughout the cooking process. It's much easier to adjust flavors gradually than to fix an over-seasoned dish.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Clean as You Cook</h3>
              <p>Wash dishes and clean up while you cook. This keeps your workspace organized and makes cleanup much less overwhelming.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Temperature Guidelines -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-thermometer-half"></i> Temperature Guidelines</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Poultry</h3>
              <p><strong>165¬∞F (74¬∞C)</strong> - This is the safe internal temperature for all poultry, including chicken, turkey, and duck.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Beef</h3>
              <p><strong>145¬∞F (63¬∞C)</strong> for medium-rare, 160¬∞F (71¬∞C) for medium, 170¬∞F (77¬∞C) for well-done.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Pork</h3>
              <p><strong>145¬∞F (63¬∞C)</strong> - Modern pork is safe at this temperature, allowing for juicy, tender results.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Fish</h3>
              <p><strong>145¬∞F (63¬∞C)</strong> - Fish should flake easily with a fork when properly cooked.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Substitution Ideas -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-exchange-alt"></i> Smart Substitutions</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Dairy Alternatives</h3>
              <p>Use lactose-free milk, almond milk, or coconut milk as 1:1 substitutes for regular milk in most recipes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Fresh vs Dried Herbs</h3>
              <p>Fresh herbs can replace dried herbs - use 3 times more fresh than dried. Dried herbs are more concentrated.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Sweetener Swaps</h3>
              <p>Maple syrup can replace honey in equal amounts. Both add moisture and sweetness to recipes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Stock Substitutions</h3>
              <p>Vegetable stock can replace chicken stock in most recipes. Use low-sodium versions to control salt levels.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Kitchen Tools -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-tools"></i> Essential Kitchen Tools</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Sharp Knives</h3>
              <p>A sharp chef's knife is safer and more efficient than a dull one. Learn proper knife skills for faster, safer prep work.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Digital Thermometer</h3>
              <p>Essential for cooking meat safely. Instant-read thermometers give you confidence in doneness levels.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Good Cutting Board</h3>
              <p>Use separate cutting boards for raw meat and vegetables to prevent cross-contamination.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Kitchen Scale</h3>
              <p>Weighing ingredients is more accurate than measuring by volume, especially for baking.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Time-Saving Tips -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-clock"></i> Time-Saving Strategies</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Batch Prep</h3>
              <p>Chop extra vegetables when you have time. Store them properly and use throughout the week.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>One-Pot Meals</h3>
              <p>Choose recipes that cook everything in one pot or pan to minimize cleanup and cooking time.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Slow Cooker Magic</h3>
              <p>Use your slow cooker for tough cuts of meat and dishes that benefit from long, slow cooking.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Freezer Meals</h3>
              <p>Double recipes and freeze half for future meals. Soups, stews, and casseroles freeze particularly well.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Holiday Cooking -->
        <div class="tip-category">
          <h2><i class="fas fa-calendar-alt"></i> Holiday Cooking Tips</h2>
          <div class="tips-grid">
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Plan Your Timeline</h3>
              <p>Work backwards from serving time. Know when each dish needs to go in the oven and plan accordingly.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Make Ahead</h3>
              <p>Prepare side dishes the day before when possible. Many casseroles and desserts improve with overnight chilling.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Use Your Oven Wisely</h3>
              <p>Group dishes by cooking temperature. Start with the longest-cooking items and work your way up.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="tip-card">
              <h3>Rest Your Meat</h3>
              <p>Let roasted meats rest for 15-30 minutes before carving. This allows juices to redistribute for better flavor.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
